1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper deals with the capacity of a communication channel in the presence of an eavesdropper, which is a classic problem in information theory. 
2. cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) - The paper deals with the problem of oblivious transfer, which is a fundamental cryptographic primitive. 
3. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) - The paper may involve complexity-theoretic arguments to prove the security of the proposed protocol. 
4. cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) - The paper may involve practical applications of the proposed protocol in secure communication systems. 
5. cs.MM (Multimedia) - The paper may involve the use of multimedia data (e.g., images, videos) in the proposed protocol.
